{
  "texts": [
    "Contrastive learning has evolved as a generic approach for learning feature representations with fewer assumptions regarding the usefulness of particular tasks.",
    "Framed succinctly, the contrastive learning problem is to produce representations that are invariant to non-meaningful transformations.",
    "In contrastive learning, g φ (h) is a neural network that outputs vector embed- dings, which need not have the same dimension as the representations h. The goal of contrastive learning is to produce embeddings z i that are very close (as measured by some distance function, d(z i, z j)) for positive pairs of examples and very far for negative pairs.",
    "SimCLR [23] is an example of a contrastive learning SSL method in which positive pairs are distorted versions of the same image and negative pairs are distorted versions of distinct images.",
    "The weights θ and φ are optimized such that the embeddings are close and far for positive and negative pairs respectively."
  ]
}